narratives.question_text:
What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: Perspective of military history and effects of politics economy for war and military.

A basic overview of military history in the West (Europe and the US) -- including the development of military technologies, the rise and fall of great powers, and economic, social, and political factors which contributed to these developments
The military history of the Western world since the 1500s.
I learned the general themes of warfare and military history of the West since 1500. Additionally, I got important writing practice.
Broad understanding of military developments from 1500-on

Knowledge: I learned about the military history of the West. I learned about the military technology and revolutions that took place from 1500-modern day, the rise and fall of states, the relationship between the military, state, and the economy, etc. 

Skills: Historical analysis and reading

Insights: The main insight I gained from this course was "why the west". Unlike some previous history courses I took, this history course did not present the West as some forever dominating, unassailable force. This course taught me what factors led to Europe to become the center of global power despite being vastly poorer and technologically poorer than other places like Asia or the Ottoman Empire.
I learned a lot about military history starting in Europe and going until the late 1900s. I now know how and why we have the wars and militaries we do today.
Argumentative and reading skills.
I learned a lot about the broad swathes of history and how multiple things affected the military history of the world.
Loved the course. Broad sweep of the big ideas behind military history from 1500-present
History of military

The course focused less on individual battles and events and more on the interaction of war and politics and what that means for state power. Themes included state consolidation in the early modern age, industrialization and its effect on war and society, the World Wars, power balances, and the military decline of the West in the modern age.

Learned all about Military History of the West: important Wars and bids for power, technological advancements, how the West became such an influential region of the world. More technically, the course involved being able to extrapolate major ideas from 75-200 pages of reading each week, and consider the readings in conjunction with one another.
I learned how to form a historical argument over. broad periods of time.
A somewhat decent knowledge base of European history with an emphasis on the wars.
Different themes in military history ranging from the rise of military strategy in the 16th century to the rapid development and dominance of air power in the 20th century.
A good survey introduction of military history (and the history of Western societies in general) since 1500.
historical synthesis
I learned how to read fast and skim and still understand the readings because there are a lot of readings
Better understanding the historical interplay between different forces and how military history is impacted and moved by different historical events to weave together a cohesive narrative.
I learned a ton about military history, state formation, and how to think about the role of the military in the broad sweep of history.
Military history
I learned about the military history of the world from 1500 on.
Learned a lot about five centuries of western history

How to write a history essay, and the complex stories of national and military development.

War made the state, and the state made war

Broad view of military history, the factors that contribute to the rise and fall of great powers, why western Europe became dominant.  Good survey course with interesting readings that makes you think about broader themes in history and the world today.
Introduction to military history
writing historical essays, basic overview of western military history
Gained insights into the ways in which war has developed since the 1500s, especially focusing on the effects of new and revolutionary technologies.

narratives.question_text:
What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: Interesting topics, thorough lectures. Although there is quite a bit of reading and idk if all of it is rlly necessary

Strengths: interesting, very chill, low workload 
Weaknesses: very broad, sometimes I felt like I wasn't learning that much new specific information interesting, very chill, sometimes the workload was so low (only a midterm and final) that I didn't feel encouraged to learn the material well

Strengths: Lecture quality, reading selection
Weaknesses: Readings piled up towards the end of the year, limited opportunities for student engagement during lecture

Strengths: pretty easy, but interesting content
Weakness: can't really think of anything
This was one of my favorite courses thus far and it is definitely worth taking if you can.

Strengths: Kennedy! Course content is great and Kennedy is an awesome lecturer. 

Weaknesses: Depending on your discussion section, the discussion can be subpar.

The problem with the course is that Prof Kennedy is super knowledgeable but it doesn't translate to you through his lectures. Almost all of the knowledge you get comes from the readings. The readings are massive (200-350 pages per week) and it's so hard to stay on top of them. I lasted about 2.5 months and then finally got behind and couldn't catch up. The class itself is basically just an incentive to do the readings which is ok I guess, as I would never have read these books without this class. My section was really good, I think better than others, so we had good conversations and reinforced key concepts.
Great course for an overview of European history post 1500.
Overall it was very good and I enjoyed the lectures and sections. Personally I thought there were too many readings so I wasn't able to get to them all.

I thought it was organized well and strong in all aspects. I liked that the final paper requirement was dropped versus previous years, I feel like the exams were enough to get the content readily absorbed.
Great lectures
The lectures by Prof. Kennedy were very interesting. This course is considered a Yale staple, and I think I got all that I expected from it without notable weaknesses.

Paul Kennedy is a fascinating lecturer and the material is super interesting. He frequently incorporates literature, art, and anecdote into lectures to keep them as spry as himself.  Result: Lectures are very enjoyable. I took this course with my suitemates and we hooked it up to our TV and watched together. Genuinely more entertaining than most sitcoms, if you enjoy history. Provides new perspective to European history. There's a lot of reading, but the final/midterm are based on big ideas, so many got by without exhausting the reading list.  I would cut out Howards War in European History. The other books all provide a certain flavor (Kennedy's pieces offer the necessary survey knowledge, and the other readings expand upon it). But that book was rather dull and added little to my understanding.
The course is well structured and provides balance across various time periods.
Not putting all the ROTC on the same section

Strengths: lectures were quite interesting.
Weaknesses: BEWARE, NOT an easy A. Many of the other course reviews come from ROTC students, and they have what is essentially a DIFFERENT VERSION of the course. To explain your course grade is determined entirely by your TA. If you get lucky and get an easy-going TA (very very few of them), you will have a good chance at an A/A-. Most TA's, however, are quite strict when grading the essay exams. The ROTC students have their OWN SECTIONS for ROTC students only, and these TA's are all SUPER EASYGOING. It's because this is a required class for the ROTC kids or something. But for the rest of us, this is NOT an easy A at all. Take the other reviews with a grain of salt.
The lectures were engaging! Kennedy is a great lecturer and this is really a class worth taking if you can fit it in.

I think Professor Kennedy and his treasure-trove of knowledge is one of the biggest strengths of this course. His ability to make connections and explain, with such detail, any event and connect economic and technological changes to these events is deeply interesting. However, I found that the biggest issue with this course is its method of 'teaching' the content to the students. While the learning is done through the readings, the lectures are used to include auxiliary details, and the discussion sections are used to further detail and connect the readings.

Very good course, and I think it is structured and laid out very well. The course wants to cover a lot of different themes and ideas, and I think it manages to successfully interplay all of them very effectively. I think the instructions and guidance was clear and effective.

This course was a fantastic way to learn about the military history of the west. It was well organized to help your learning, and the material was fascinating. 

The real weakness was the absurd reading load occasionally as high as 150 pages for each lecture.
Very monotonous lectures - Professor Kennedy is incredible and obviously and expert in his field, but very monotone lectures without much variation. Interesting material though.
This course was very interesting but could be more engaging

Professor Kennedy is fantastically charismatic. His lectures were great, albeit not as information dense as they could have been.

The readings were phenomenal. The diversity of views (from Boot to Kennedy himself) was super useful. But I think there was too much reading, which made it difficult to focus in on anything. Rarely was I caught up on the material. I think Boot, McNeill, and the Kennedy readings, plus the occasional Canvas supplement (On War was fascinating), were more than enough. Howard was good for the pre-class readings as well. I think if we had stuck to these readings it would have been more manageable.

Then for the discussion sections, I think this was a fluke, but mine was a bit small. Only 4 people! That made things slow at times.

Strength: covers a sweeping geographic and timescale in history; interesting readings; engaging professor

Weaknesses: learning dependent on section; sporadic lecture topics and high reading load can leave student confused; not as much in depth analysis/critical thinking involved as I would have liked.

The lecture material is innately interesting and Professor Kennedy is a fantastic lecturer. I felt like there was a lot of overlap between the readings, which were often onerous, so streamlining the assigned readings would have been helpful. Also, I didn't like that the vast majority of the final grade was based on two exams. Having a paper worth ~20-30% of the final grade could potentially be useful, especially because it would allow for more creative/nuanced analysis of the course material (which is simply impossible in a short exam essay).

Strengths: Prof. Kennedy is awesome.  He is the archetype of a Yale history professor and makes the lectures engaging.  Course structure was well thought out with many people supporting.
Weaknesses: Sometimes easy to forget readings but easy enough to get by without them.

narratives.question_text: Among the practices in this course geared toward learning during the COVID-19 pandemic, which succeeded and which could be improved? Please comment on course practices that allowed for virtual engagement. (Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: Lectures were really good but I think the readings were somewhat too much
I think it adjusted really well. The assessments also worked well with the online format
Having lecture recorded was the biggest positive.
It was a relatively standard virtual lecture but I thought it worked fine.
Virtual lectures were good
Recording lectures worked very well, especially for studying for tests.

Paul Kennedy taught this class as if it were in person, except that the assessments were open book and cut down somewhat. Glad the assessments were open book because it eliminated the threat of cheating, and that some elements of the exam (IDs) were cut down. TA's and Professor were accommodating and flexible.
All good!
This went about as good as can be expected.
The uploading of the lectures was absolutely necessary. Good call!
I didn't feel like the class was hampered at all by the virtual format. Everything seemed to go smoothly.
I would have enjoyed more flexible attendance and knowing lecture was going to be recorded every day.

narratives.question_text:
Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: Yes gives excellent perspective and view of military and power of world.
maybe! it won't change your life or anything, but there's no reason not to take it! pretty gutty, and Professor Kennedy is kind of a legend
Yes - Prof Kennedy is an amazing and unique lecturer with a wide grasp of military and historical knowledge
Work is very manageable so long as you stay up on readings. Exams are not terribly difficult. Prof Kennedy is excellent, and lectures well.
if ur looking for a gut and want a broad-strokes understanding of military history, sure. Don't take this class if you're interested in tactics

There is a lot of reading for this course (several hundred pages each week) and it can be really dense and dreadful if you are not interested in military history. For me, this class was great because I love military history and I enjoy learning about it in my free time anyways. You will have to decide for yourself it is what you want, but it might be worth a credit/d/fail if you can't put your full effort in.

I would definitely recommend this course to other students! It is impossible to understand the West and where we are in the world today without learning about military history. While military history might not be everyone's cup of tea, the modern world is built from conflicts which the course covers extensively. Kennedy is a thoughtful lecturer who will tries to expose everyone to the "bigger picture" of the things you learn from the readings, which I loved.
I would recommend it if you are interested in military history, I am, and I'm glad I took it. Do be warned that it is a lot of reading.
Yes it is a good intro history class.
Yes I would, I thought it was interesting and well-taught. I liked looking at military history through broad trends instead of focusing on small battles.
Take the course. The TA problems mentioned in previous years have been fixed. Section is great (first one I've ever liked going to), lecture is good, and the readings are excellent.
Yes

Yes, this course is considered a Yale staple, and I think I got all that I expected from it without notable weaknesses. Note that the reading is actually quite extensive for a large and popular History course, but you only really need to do enough reading to understand the nuances of lecture and to participate well in sections.
Yes. This course is extremely fun and interesting. Professor Kennedy does a great job during lecture and the weekly readings are intriguing.

Absolutely!  Overall, my favorite history course thus far, I'm shocked it isn't reviewed as highly. If you want to listen to a charming British man talk about Picasso and B-52s in the same breath, this is your course. If you want to read about how Italian cities are designed to repel invaders, why it didn't matter that Britain lost the American Revolution, spend an hour or so on a colorful battle like Koniggratz or Tsushima,  or learn about the cannons and swords and atom bombs that changed the world -- this is your course!
I would recommend this course as it provides a sweeping view of military history and international affairs.
Yes! Professor Kennedy is such an interesting person.
absolutely! I learned so much and really enjoyed listening to lectures.

NOT IF YOU WANT AN EASY A. Again this is not a gut. Many of the other course reviews come from ROTC students, and they have what is essentially a DIFFERENT VERSION of the course. To explain your course grade is determined entirely by your TA. If you get lucky and get an easy-going TA (very very few of them), you will have a good chance at an A/A-. Most TA's, however, are quite strict when grading the essay exams. The ROTC students have their OWN SECTIONS for ROTC students only, and these TA's are all SUPER EASYGOING. It's because this is a required class for the ROTC kids or something. But for the rest of us, this is NOT an easy A at all. Take the other reviews with a grain of salt.

Yes, it is always interesting to listen to Professor Kennedy talk about military history. He has perfected his lectures such that they would always last exactly 50 minutes. This course could make a very interesting podcast as there are many insightful and broad topics that would help anyone understand the complexity of state powers.
Yes! You should really take this class if you have any internet in Military History at all. It is one of the few survey history classes that Yale actually offers.

I would recommend this course to another student, but would caution them that this course has a relative low level of engagement, at least when taught during the COVID-19 pandemic. The primary learning from this course would be done by oneself through the readings, and this learning would be expounded upon mainly through the discussion sections.

Furthermore, I would recommend that this student take another European history course before this course to provide better context to the events and factors discussed.

Yes! I think this course is important for any incoming Yale student to take, because it really gets at a lot of different ideas and applications: politics, economics, morality and warfare. I think these ideas are highly motivating and important, and I think it would be a really great idea for any incoming Yale student to do!

I would absolutely recommend this course. I am a military history fan, so am of course biased, but the material is fascinating, Kennedy is a delight, and the workload is in all honesty not particularly high. There is a lot of reading, so be aware of that, but other than that (and not all of it is strictly needed) the work is very low. Great way to learn a fascinating topic.
If they are interested in European military history
Yes I would it is very interesting and a lighter workload
Yes 100% if Polly is the TA and Prof Kennedy is teaching
Absolutely. It provides a lens of understanding of history that is just totally absent elsewhere. Professor Kennedy is doing fantastic work by keeping this intellectual strand alive at Yale.
Yes

Absolutely! Professor Kennedy is an amazing lecturer and if you are interested in the subject matter, there is a great deal of extra information in the readings. Polly was also an incredible TF, and her discussion sections took the class to another level. Be aware that the vast majority of the final grade comes from a midterm + final exam so there is little room for error correction as the class moves forward.

Yes--just an enjoyable course.  Probably not the most challenging class you'll take in the history department, but satisfying all around.  Prof. Kennedy is great, the TAs are great, the information is entertaining.  Allow yourself to take a class that is actually enjoyable.
